{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fc684914-9d34-4022-bb83-cd5a6d2f1dda","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. For **analyzing** an existing `.dmp` file, here are the recommended tools:\n\n**`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer: `clrstack`, `pe` (print exception), `dumpheap`, `gcroot`.\n\n**Other options:**\n- **Visual Studio** – open the `.dmp` directly for mixed-mode debugging\n- **lldb + SOS** (Linux/macOS) – `dotnet-sos install`, then `lldb --core your-file.dmp`\n- **WinDbg** (Windows) – load SOS with `.loadby sos coreclr`\n\n**Quick triage tip** — start with `pe` (print exception) in `dotnet-dump analyze` to see if there's an unhandled exception with a stack trace. That's usually the fastest path to a root cause.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e1e4b327-b2fb-4be8-9e9f-89d190fb4d85","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here. The user wants to analyze an existing dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing crash dumps without invoking the skill.","outputTokens":391},"id":"5345ac7c-1a19-493c-a15c-897873ba2e7e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:08:32.177Z","parentId":"a954a1c5-9424-45f4-9f84-b2e94962555a"}
